JOHANNESBURG Google is celebrating 40 years of hip-hop with a customised doodle.The search engine is on Friday putting search users in an interactive DJ booth.Users can click for a chance to mix their own samples from legendary hip-hop tracks.READ: Google Doodle lets you create calming musical animationsAccording to Google, "In the 1970s, an underground urban movement known as 'hip-hop' began to develop in the South Bronx in New York City. It focused on emceeing (or MCing) over 'breakbeats', house parties and neighbourhood block party events, held outdoors. ... On August 11, 1973 DJ Kool Herc was the DJ at his sister's back-to-school party. The new doodle was designed by legendary graffiti artist and founding creative director of Def Jam records Cey Adams.According to the Business Insider, Adams said he was excited by the opportunity to put a graffiti-style logo on the Google home page and have people all over the world see it. eNCA